Press.</li>

<li>Kubala, R., forthcoming, &ldquo;Aesthetic Blame&rdquo;,
<em>Journal of the American Philosophical Association</em>.</li>

<li>Lacey, N. and H. Pickard, 2021, &ldquo;Why Standing to Blame May
Be Lost but Authority to Hold Accountable Retained: Criminal Law as a
Regulative Public Institution&rdquo;, <em>The Monist</em>, 104:
265&ndash;280.</li>

<li>Lippert-Rasmussen, K., 2024, <em>The Beam and the Mote: On Blame,
Standing, and Normativity</em>, New York: Oxford University
Press.</li>

<li>Macnamara, C., 2011, &ldquo;Holding Others Responsible&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 152: 81&ndash;102.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2015, &ldquo;Reactive Attitudes as
Communicative Entities&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy and Phenomenological
Research</em>, 90: 546&ndash;569.</li>

<li>Matheson, B. and P. Milam, 2022, &ldquo;The Case Against Non-Moral
Blame&rdquo;, in M. Timmons (ed.), <em>Oxford Studies in Normative
Ethics</em> (Volume 11), Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Mason, E., 2019, <em>Ways to be Blameworthy: Rightness, Wrongness,
and Responsibility</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Mason, M., 2011, &ldquo;Blame: Taking it Seriously&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy and Phenomenological Research</em>, 83:
473&ndash;481.</li>

<li>McCormick, K., 2022, <em>The Problem of Blame: Making Sense of
Moral Anger</em>, New York: Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>McGeer, V., 2013, &ldquo;Civilizing Blame&rdquo;, in Coates &amp;
Tognazzini (eds.) 2013: 162&ndash;188.</li>

<li>McKenna, M., 2012, <em>Conversation and Responsibility</em>, New
York: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Mele, A., 2011, &ldquo;Moral Responsibility for Actions: Epistemic
and Freedom Conditions&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Explorations</em>,
13: 101&ndash;111.</li>

<li>Menges, L., 2017, &ldquo;The Emotion Account of Blame,&rdquo;
<em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 174: 257&ndash;273.</li>

<li>Nagel, T., 1998, &ldquo;Concealment and Exposure&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy and Public Affairs</em>, 27: 3&ndash;30.</li>

<li>Nelkin, D., 2011, <em>Making Sense of Freedom and
Responsibility</em>, New York: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2015, &ldquo;Psychopaths, Incorrigible
Racists, and the Faces of Responsibility&rdquo;, <em>Ethics</em>, 125:
357&ndash;390.</li>

<li>Nussbaum, M. C., 2016, <em>Anger and Forgiveness: Resentment,
Generosity, Justice</em>, New York: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>O&rsquo;Brien, M., 2022, &ldquo;Easy for You to Say&rdquo;,
<em>Australasian Journal of Philosophy</em>, 100: 429&ndash;442.</li>

<li>Pereboom, D., 2021, <em>Wrongdoing and the Moral Emotions</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Pickard, H., 2013, &ldquo;Irrational Blame&rdquo;,
<em>Analysis</em>, 73: 613&ndash;626.</li>

<li>Piovarchy, A., 2020, &ldquo;Hypocrisy, Standing to Blame, and
Second-Personal Authority&rdquo;, <em>Pacific Philosophical
